In your current setup, the `Suspense` component is wrapping the entire `Template` component, but it doesn't seem to be directly tied to any asynchronous operation that would trigger a fallback UI. The `searchImages` function is an asynchronous operation, but it is not directly integrated with the `Suspense` mechanism.

To properly use `Suspense` for data fetching, you would typically need to use a library or approach that supports concurrent rendering, such as React's experimental features or a library like `react-query` or `swr`. These libraries can integrate with `Suspense` to show fallback content while data is being fetched.

If your intention is to show a loading state while images are being fetched, you might want to manage this with a local loading state instead. Here's a simple example of how you could implement this:

```tsx
export default function GalleryPage() {
  const userImager = useImageService();
  const [images, setImages] = useState<ImageClass[]>([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState<boolean>(true);

  const searchImages = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    try {
      const resultImages = await userImager.getImages();
      setImages(resultImages);
    } catch (error) {
      console.log("Error getting images:", error);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    searchImages();
  }, []);

  return (
    <Template>
      <button
        className={
          "h-auto w-auto cursor-pointer rounded-full bg-gray-700 p-2 text-3xl"
        }
        onClick={searchImages}
      >
        Teste
      </button>
      <h1 className="mb-4 text-center text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-700">
        Gallery Page
      </h1>
      {loading ? (
        <div>Carregando Imagens</div>
      ) : (
        <section className={"grid grid-cols-3 gap-6"}>
          {images.map((image: ImageEntity) => (
            <ImageCard
              key={image.url}
              src={image.url}
              title={image.name}
              size={image.size}
              dataUpload={new Date(image.uploadDate)}
            />
          ))}
        </section>
