In your `GalleryPage` component, you might consider using `useMemo` in the following scenarios:

1. **Memoizing Derived Data**: If you have any derived data that is computationally expensive to calculate from `images`, you can use `useMemo` to memoize that calculation. For example, if you need to filter or sort the images, you can memoize the result.

2. **Memoizing Components**: If you have a component that receives props derived from `images` and is expensive to render, you can use `useMemo` to memoize the component itself.

Here's an example of how you might use `useMemo` to memoize a filtered list of images:

```typescript
import { useMemo } from "react";

// Inside your GalleryPage component
const filteredImages = useMemo(() => {
  // Example: Filter images based on some condition
  return images.filter(image => image.size > 1000); // Example condition
}, [images]);

// Use filteredImages in your component
<section className={"grid grid-cols-3 gap-6"}>
  {filteredImages.map((image: ImageEntity) => (
    <ImageCard
      key={image.id}
      src={image.url}
      title={image.name}
      size={image.size}
      dataUpload={new Date(image.uploadDate)}
    />
  ))}
</section>
```

In this example, `filteredImages` will only be recalculated when the `images` array changes, which can help improve performance if the filtering operation is expensive.

If you don't have any expensive calculations or operations in your component, you might not need to use `useMemo` at all. It's important to use it only when necessary to avoid adding unnecessary complexity to your code."}],"context":{"currentFile":{"path":"src/app/gallery/page.tsx","fsPath":"/home/carlos/Documentos/Projects/interface-project-react-spring/src/app/gallery/page.tsx","sources":["opened_tab"],"content":""use client";

